  "story": {
    "lead": "The UK House of Commons has voted down an amendment to transfer the EU's protocol on animal sentience into UK law, leading to confusion and protests from animal rights groups who fear the UK is backtracking on recognizing animals as sentient beings. However, MPs deny this interpretation, stating the vote was about legal procedure, not the principle of animal sentience.",
    "details": [
      "The amendment, part of the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill, was defeated 313 votes to 295 on November 15. Green Party co-leader Caroline Lucas had proposed the amendment to incorporate Article 13 of the Lisbon Treaty, which recognizes animals as sentient beings.",
      "Tory MPs argue that the defeat doesn't signal a change in policy, as UK law already protects animals as sentient beings. For instance, Tory MP Zac Goldsmith called some reporting on the vote 'weird and dishonest,' tweeting that the vote was about ensuring the correct legal procedure for animal welfare standards, not the principle of sentience.",
      "Rachel Maclean, another Conservative MP, addressed the confusion through a video, asserting that all governments are committed to protecting animals' sentience, a law already embedded in UK legislation. Prime Minister Theresa May also supported this view, declaring that the government 'recognises and respects that animals are sentient beings.'",
      "Animal rights groups and veterinarians are alarmed. The British Veterinary Association's senior vice-president, Gudrun Ravetz, stated that the vote 'undermines the government’s previous promises' of maintaining high animal welfare standards post-Brexit. Multiple online petitions and public figures' criticism have ensued.",
      "Some MPs, like Conservative Henry Smith, argue that EU laws still allow practices criticized by animal rights groups, suggesting that the amendment isn't a panacea. Meanwhile, Green MP Caroline Lucas highlighted that the UK had originally championed the EU's recognition of animal sentience during its presidency in 1997.",
      "The conflict seems to stem from differing interpretations of the vote's implications, with clarifications from some MPs and reliable sources possibly not reaching the wider public, leading to misunderstanding and outrage. The coming days might see further debate in the House of Lords, where the withdrawal bill will also be considered."
    ]
  }
}

