  "article": {
    "title": "Kezia Dugdale Defends Reality Show Appearance, Donates Fee to Homeless Charity",
    "content": "The former Scottish Labour leader, Kezia Dugdale, has pledged to donate part of her fee from appearing in the ITV reality show “I’m a Celebrity... Get Me Out of Here” to a homeless charity, defending her controversial decision amid backlash from Labour colleagues. Dugdale rebuffed complaints from fellow Labour MSPs at Holyrood who likened her participation to taking a second job, insisting instead that her appearance is a valuable use of her time as an elected official.\n\nSpeaking to Australian show-business reporters, Dugdale addressed criticism that her involvement in the high-profile TV programme could be seen as seeking personal financial gain. She admitted to being “well paid” for the stint but maintained that it does not constitute a secondary occupation. Her participation in the show, which is currently filming in Australia, follows a public dispute with other Labour politicians in Scotland who have questioned the appropriateness of her time and resources being used for such an endeavour.\n\nTo offset the controversy, Dugdale has designated a portion of her earnings—equivalent to three weeks’ salary as an MSP—to the Rock Trust homeless charity. This move clarifies an earlier misreporting that suggested she was donating to a motor neurone disease campaign instead. The Scottish Labour leader launched a Twitter feed (@TeamKez) portraying her in a Rock Trust T-shirt, filming a message to her constituents. In the video, she empathetically acknowledged the controversy, stating, “I appreciate that to quite a few of my constituents, this is quite a controversial move. I know there will be people upset about it.”\n\nDugdale emphasized the educational potential of the show, which reaches millions of viewers, underscoring her intention to discuss politics and Labour values with young audiences. The Daily Record, for which she writes as a columnist, cited Dugdale as asserting, “I have a record of giving money to charity. This isn’t a second job, this is three weeks out of my work.” Through her explanation, she strived to reconcile her activism with political engagement via unconventional means, employing the widespread appeal of reality television to amplify her message."
  }
}
```

