    "title": "Government unveils industrial strategy to boost R&D, address productivity gaps",
    "content": ">**The world is changing** as new technologies disrupt traditional economies. The impending exit from the European Union will reshape trade, movement of goods and people, and our global positioning. These forward-looking questions, often sidelined by governments in favor of markets, globalization, and EU governance, now demand proactive solutions. The government is set to release its industrial strategy white paper next Monday, with details to be highlighted during this week’s budget. A promising step is Theresa May’s announcement to boost public and private R&D investment by up to £80bn over the next decade. Additionally, the UK will allocate £1.7bn to enhance city regional transport links. These initiatives aim to tackle entrenched challenges such as subpar productivity, uneven regional development, and a shortfall in converting knowledge into widespread wealth. The 2008 financial crisis and the Brexit decision have worsened these structural issues. The UK urgently requires a long-term industrial strategy focusing on R&D and connectivity to address these national problems."
  }
}

